/*
          final Keyword in Java

The final keyword in Java is used to make something fixed or unchangeable.

It can be used with:

Variable
Method
Class
1. Final Variable

A final variable cannot be changed after assigning a value.

Example
class Demo {

    final int speed = 100;

    void display() {

        // speed = 200; ❌ Error

        System.out.println(speed);
    }
}
Output
100
Explanation
final int speed = 100;
speed becomes constant
Value cannot be modified later
2. Final Method

A final method cannot be overridden in a child class.

Example
class Parent {

    final void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent Method");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {

    // void show() {} ❌ Error
}
Explanation
Child class cannot change the parent method implementation.
3. Final Class

A final class cannot be inherited.

Example
final class Animal {

    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal Sound");
    }
}

// class Dog extends Animal {} ❌ Error
Explanation
No class can extend a final class.
Real-Life Example
Keyword Use	Real-Life Meaning
final variable	Fixed value like PI
final method	Rule cannot be changed
final class	Fully secured class
Important Points
Type	Meaning
final variable	Value cannot change
final method	Cannot override
final class	Cannot inherit
Example with Constant
class Test {

    final double PI = 3.14;

    void area() {

        double r = 5;

        double result = PI * r * r;

        System.out.println(result);
    }
}
Advantages of final

✅ Security
✅ Prevent modification
✅ Create constants
✅ Improve code safety

Simple Definition

The final keyword is used to restrict changes in Java.
 */